# Accessibility (always)

Every UI change must keep the site usable for keyboard, screen reader, and
low-vision users. Treat accessibility as part of "done," not a follow-up.

## Always do

- **Semantic HTML first**: use `<button>`, `<a>`, `<nav>`, `<header>`,
  `<main>`, `<section>`, `<ul>/<li>`, headings in order. Don't make a `<div>`
  clickable when a `<button>`/`<a>` fits.
- **Label every control**: inputs/selects need an associated `<label htmlFor>`.
  Icon-only controls need `aria-label` (e.g. the hamburger, flag emoji).
- **Keyboard operable**: everything works with Tab/Enter/Space. Don't put
  focusable elements in hidden/collapsed regions without `tabIndex={-1}`.
- **Visible focus**: keep `focus-visible:ring-*` styles; never remove outlines
  without a replacement.
- **State to assistive tech**: use `aria-expanded`/`aria-controls` on toggles,
  `aria-hidden` on decorative/collapsed content, `aria-live` for dynamic text
  (e.g. the results summary).
- **Color contrast**: text must meet WCAG AA (~4.5:1). Don't rely on color
  alone — pair it with text/icon (e.g. "Under budget" + dot, not just green).
- **Respect motion**: heavy animations should honor `prefers-reduced-motion`.

## Example

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — clickable div, no label, no focus state
<div onClick={toggle}>☰</div>

// ✅ GOOD — real button, labeled, keyboard + focus ready
<button
  type="button"
  onClick={toggle}
  aria-label={open ? "Close menu" : "Open menu"}
  aria-expanded={open}
  className="focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-brand-400"
>
  <span aria-hidden="true">☰</span>
</button>
```
